---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AI Control Plane Prototyping | hackall360"
  description="Composing a neuro-symbolic control plane that blends agentic orchestration, retrieval meshes, and live telemetry to launch resilient AI services."
>
  <div class="mx-auto flex max-w-4xl flex-col gap-12 px-6 py-24 sm:px-10 lg:py-28">
    <header class="space-y-6 text-slate-200">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.5em] text-accent-light/80">// initiative Â· ai control planes</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold text-white sm:text-5xl">Composing neuro-symbolic control planes.</h1>
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-300 sm:text-lg">
        Q4 2025 is all about engineering an adaptive execution fabric. Retrieval-augmented context meshes feed agentic
        planners, telemetry streams gate deployments in near real time, and human operators keep a supervisory loop on the
        runtime posture.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="space-y-4 rounded-3xl border border-slate-800/60 bg-slate-950/40 p-8 text-slate-200">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Quarter objectives</h2>
      <ul class="list-disc space-y-3 pl-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
        <li>Design a modular inference lattice that fans out to specialized agents while keeping lineage and audit streams intact.</li>
        <li>Prototype a policy-driven router that can swap between neural, symbolic, and retrieval pathways without operator downtime.</li>
        <li>Expose a telemetry-first operator console that couples trace overlays with mitigation playbooks.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-6 rounded-3xl border border-slate-800/60 bg-slate-950/30 p-8 text-slate-200">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Technical threads in flight</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-800/60 bg-slate-950/50 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">Retrieval mesh</h3>
          <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            Building a knowledge graph-backed retrieval layer that can shape prompts per service and persist execution context
            across long-running sessions. Vector indexes, symbolic tagging, and runtime heuristics coordinate to keep the
            planner grounded.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-800/60 bg-slate-950/50 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">Orchestration spine</h3>
          <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            A resilient scheduler manages agent swarms, spans auto-scaling pools, and asserts guardrails before the first token
            emits. Each run surfaces deterministic checkpoints so humans can intercede or let the automation surge ahead.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-800/60 bg-slate-950/50 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">Observability runway</h3>
          <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            Instrumenting the stack with span-level provenance, reinforcement learning metrics, and user feedback loops so the
            control plane keeps compounding accuracy while staying transparent.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-4 rounded-3xl border border-slate-800/60 bg-slate-950/40 p-8 text-slate-200">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">Next checkpoints</h2>
      <ul class="list-disc space-y-3 pl-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
        <li>Ship a reference deployment that can be exercised by the tabletop drills to validate failover and guardrails.</li>
        <li>Draft integration hooks for the upcoming agentic workflow accelerators so the same spine powers both human and autonomous lanes.</li>
        <li>Publish instrumentation specs that downstream teams can reuse when porting the control plane to new environments.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
